year_prod = df.groupby('year')['prodvalue'].sum()
year= df["year"].unique()
x= year_prod
y= year
plt.pie(x,labels=y,autopct='%1.1f%%')

4. Plot and Understand the distribution of the variable "price per lb" using displot, and write your findings.¶

In [43]:
sns.displot(df['priceperlb'], kde=True)
plt.title('Distribution of Price per lb')
plt.xlabel('Price')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
Out[43]:
Text(4.944444444444445, 0.5, 'Frequency')
1. The most common price is 1.5¶
2. The least commom price is 4.0¶
3. Price per Lb around 4.0 occoures minimum times¶
4.The average price would be around between 2 and 2.25¶
5.From the histogram we can observe that the data is positively skewed¶

7. Visualize and understand the relationship between the multiple pairs of variables throughout different years using pairplot and add your inferences. (use columns 'numcol', 'yield percol', 'total prod', 'prodvalue','year')¶

In [44]:
sns.pairplot(df[['numcol', 'yieldpercol', 'totalprod', 'prodvalue','year']], hue='year');
1. The datas of 'numcol', 'totalprod' and 'prodvalue' are positively skewed.¶
2. Data in 'yieldpercol' seems to be normally distributed\¶
3. As the total production increases, the production value and stocks are also increases.¶

8. Display the correlation values using a plot and add your inferences. (use columns 'numcol', 'yield percol', 'total prod', 'stocks', 'price per lb', 'prodvalue')¶

sns.heatmap(data=df[['numcol', 'yieldpercol', 'totalprod', 'stocks', 'priceperlb', 'prodvalue']].corr(),annot=True)

2. The relationship between numcol and stocks is positive correlation and correlation value is 0.83.¶

4. The relationship between total production and production value is positive correlation and correlation value is 0.91.¶
5. The relationship between total production and stocks is positive correlation and correlation value is 0.88.¶
6. The relationship between stocks and production value is positive correlation and correlation value is 0.73.¶
